,"1293–1361":"1293–1361","1271–1313":"1271–1313","1312–1373":"1312–1373","1237–1280":"1237–1280","–Female":"Deceased","1237":"1237","1313":"1313","1312":"1312","1298":"1298","1373":"1373","1361":"1361","Abt 1312":"about 1312","before 1272":"before 1272","1271":"1271","1293":"1293","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Hornby, Lancashire, England":"Hornby, Lancashire, England","St Laurence in Thanet, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"St Laurence in Thanet, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Melling, Lancashire, England":"Melling, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Byron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Byram (Yorkshire), named with Old English <i>bȳrum</i> ‘at the cattle sheds’, dative plural of <i>bȳre</i> ‘byre’. This name has occasionally been adopted as a Jewish surname, presumably as an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish name."],"variants":[{"name":"Byrom","meanings":["English: variant of   Byron  ."]},{"name":"Byrum","meanings":["English: variant of   Byron  ."]},{"name":"Byram","meanings":["English: variant of   Byron  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel Byron was born in 1270, in Melling, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Robert de Byron of Melling Manor and wife Robert de Byron. She married Robert Neville in 1298, in Hornby, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1270–":"1270–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1293–1361":"1293–1361","1271–1313":"1271–1313","1312–1373":"1312–1373","1237–1280":"1237–1280","–Female":"Surnud","1237":